                <p>
                    The first generation of <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPod" title="iPod">iPod</a> was released October 23, 2001. The major innovation of the <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPod" title="iPod">iPod</a> was its small size achieved by using a 1.8" hard drive compared to the 2.5" drives common to players at that time. The capacity of the first generation <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPod" title="iPod">iPod</a> ranged from 5G to 10 Gigabytes. The <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPod" title="iPod">iPod</a> sold for US$399 and more than 100,000 <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPod" title="iPod">iPod</a>s were sold before the end of 2001. The introduction of the <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPod" title="iPod">iPod</a> resulted in <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Jobs" title="apple">Apple Inc</a> becoming a major player in the music industry. Also, the <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPod" title="iPod">iPod</a>'s success prepared the way for the <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ITunes" title="itunes">iTunes</a> music store and the <a hre="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPhone" title="iphone">iPhone</a>. After the 1st generation of <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPod" title="iPod">iPod</a>, <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Jobs" title="apple">Apple Inc</a> released the hard drive-based <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPod" title="iPod">iPod</a> Classic, the touchscreen <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPod" title="iPod">iPod</a> Touch, video-capable <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPod" title="iPod">iPod</a> Nano, screenless <a class="anc" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IPod" title="iPod">iPod</a> Shuffle in the following years.

